> What do rational expectations of prices refer to?
**assistant**:
> Rational expectations of prices refer to the theory that individuals' expectations of future prices are based on their best available information and are therefore rational. This theory suggests that individuals will not be consistently surprised by unexpected changes in prices and that market prices will reflect all publicly available information. It is a key concept in macroeconomics and is often used to analyze the behavior of markets and the effectiveness of monetary and fiscal policy.
> 
