> What is the justification for using a linear combination of recent prices to forecast future prices?
**assistant**:
> The justification for using a linear combination of recent prices to forecast future prices is that it is often assumed that the underlying process that generates prices is stationary. Stationarity means that the statistical properties of the time series such as the mean, variance, and autocovariance do not change over time. This assumption allows to use linear models such as the autoregressive (AR) or moving average (MA) models to forecast future prices. Additionally, linear models are relatively simple and easy to estimate, interpret and forecast. They are also widely used in practice because they perform well in many cases, and are easy to implement.
> 
> However, it is important to note that this approach is based on assumptions and may not always provide accurate forecasts. In particular, it assumes that the relationship between past and future prices is linear, which may not be the case in some markets. Also, it assumes that the time series is stationary and doesn't take into account any structural breaks or changes in the underlying process that generates prices.
