> Why would future prices be a linear combination of recent prices under rational expectations?
**assistant**:
> The assumption that future prices will be a linear combination of recent prices under rational expectations is based on the idea that market participants have access to the same information and that they use this information to form their expectations. This implies that the future price will be a function of the current price, and a set of exogenous variables that are believed to influence the price. The linearity assumption comes from the idea that this function is linear, which means that the influence of each variable on the future price is constant and can be measured by a set of coefficients.
> 
> This linear combination of recent prices and exogenous variables is also based on the assumption of market efficiency, which states that prices reflect all publicly available information. This implies that past prices contain information about the future, and that this information can be used to forecast future prices. Under this assumption, market participants will use the information from past prices and other available information to form their expectations, leading to a linear relationship between past and future prices.
> 
> However, it is important to note that this assumption is based on a number of simplifying assumptions, and may not always hold in practice. Additionally, this linearity assumption is a simplification of real-world scenarios, and even in efficient markets, it's not guaranteed that the relationship between past and future prices is linear.
